ist studies. Looking beyond little magazines and other periodicals, this collection highlights the importance of book publishers in the diffusion of modernism. It also participates in the transnational turn in modernist studies, demonstrating that book publishers created new markets for modernist texts in the United States, Europe and the rest of the world.Key Features:The first volume on Anglo-American book publishers that sold difficult modernist texts to a wide range of readers around the worldSheds new light on the relationship between publishers and major modernist writersIncludes essays of broad significance written in an accessible proseDraws on extensive work in neglected archives  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aLiterature publishingxHistory. 0aModernism (Literature). 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh1 aAguirre, Mercedes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnhisel, Greg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBattershill, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClements, Amy Root, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, John Xiros, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlass, Loren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuy, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJaillant, Lise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKotin, Joshua, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSorensen, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSperling, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTurner, Catherine